VEXATA QUAESTIO. Lat. A vexed
question; a question often agitated or discussed, but not determined or settled: a question or point which has been differently determined, and so left doubtful. 7 Coke, 450;
8 Burrows, 1547.

VIRES. Lat. (The plural of “ris.’’) Powers; forces; capabilities; natural powers;
powers granted or limited. See ULTRA
VIRES.


Vires acquirit eundo. It gains strength
by continuance. Mann v. Mann’s Ex’rs, 1}
Johns. Ch. (N. Y.) 231, 237.

VIVARY. In English law. A place for
keeping wild animals alive, including fishes;
a fish pond, park, or warren.
